---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-13",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-13",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the paperclip test for a PSU?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The paperclip test bridges the PS_ON pin (pin 16, green wire) and a COM/GND pin (black wire) on the 24-pin motherboard connector to turn the PSU on without plugging it into a motherboard."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="How to Test a PSU: Safety Checklist & Testing Guide — PSUCheck"
  description="Learn how to troubleshoot and test your power supply unit safely. Explains the paperclip test method, multi-meter usage, and digital PSU testers."
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <article class="guide-article">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="guide-header">
        <div class="guide-meta">
          <span class="badge badge-safe">✓ E-E-A-T Verified</span>
          <span>Updated: July 13, 2026</span>
        </div>
        <h1>How to Test a PSU Safely</h1>
        <p class="guide-lead">
          Troubleshooting PC boot failures requires validating if the power supply works.
          This guide provides step-by-step instructions for testing a PSU at home.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="guide-layout">
        <main class="guide-content" id="main-content">
          <h2>Visual Inspections</h2>
          <p>
            Before doing electrical tests, turn off the AC power switch and disconnect the wall cord.
            Check all internal modular cable pins for thermal damage, discoloration, or loose pinouts.
          </p>

          <h2>The Paperclip Test (Basic Jumpstart)</h2>
          <p>
            This test verifies if the PSU turns on its internal fan and supplies stand-by current:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>Unplug all modular connections from motherboard, GPU, and drives.</li>
            <li>Take a standard paperclip, shape it into a U, and locate the <strong>24-pin ATX connector</strong>.</li>
            <li>Insert one end into <strong>Pin 16 (PS_ON, green wire)</strong> and the other into any adjacent <strong>COM pin (black wire, ground)</strong>.</li>
            <li>Plug the AC wall cord in and turn on the PSU switch. The fan should spin up (unless in Zero-RPM silent mode).</li>
          </ol>
          <div class="important-warning">
            <strong>⚠ Safety Rule:</strong> Never stick fingers or metal tools inside the PSU chassis holes.
            High-voltage capacitors retain dangerous electrical charges for hours after power-off.
          </div>

          <h2>Digital Tester Verification</h2>
          <p>
            For exact rail measurements (+12V, +5V, +3.3V), purchase a cheap 24-pin LCD digital PSU tester.
            It provides instantaneous voltage readings, flagging rail tolerances (should remain within ±5% specs).
          </p>

          <div style="margin-top:3rem;">
            <a href="/psu-calculator" class="btn btn-primary">Check system diagnostics</a>
          </div>
        </main>

        <aside class="guide-sidebar">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Calculators</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/psu-calculator">⚡ PSU Calculator</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pc-builder">🖥️ PC Build Cost Calculator</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Other Guides</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/guides/psu-lifespan">PSU Lifespan & Aging</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/psu-sizing-guide">PSU Sizing Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/psu-coil-whine">PSU Coil Whine Guide</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
.guide-article { padding: 4rem 0; }
.guide-header { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
.guide-meta { display:flex; gap: 1rem; align-items:center; font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-tertiary); margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
.guide-lead { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--text-secondary); max-width: 65ch; line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 0.5rem; }
.guide-layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 3rem; }
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .guide-layout { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 8fr) minmax(0, 4fr); }
}
.guide-content h2 { margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content p, .guide-content li { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
.important-warning { background: var(--color-surface-raised); border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent-orange); padding: 1rem; border-radius: var(--radius-md); margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
.guide-sidebar { display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap: 1.5rem; }
.guide-sidebar .card { padding: 1.25rem; }
</style>
